text:
over the weekend, #donaldtrump claimed that #conservatives in #california are so upset about so-called "sanctuary cities" that the right has launched "riots." during a brief q&a with reporters at the #whitehouse yesterday, a reporter asked where, exactly, these riots are taking place.
.
"take a look,"Â he replied, adding, "it is rioting in some cases.".
.
it was odd to see a sitting president point to american riots that apparently exist only in his imagination, but that wasn't the strangest exchange with reporters. the #republican also said over the weekend that he and congressional #republicans are working "around the clock" onÂ a new tax cut, which he suggested we'd see no later than nov. 1, despite the fact that congress is effectively out of session. yesterday, trumpÂ tried to explainÂ what he's talking about.

q: you said "lower tax cuts." you said that you wanted tax cuts by november 1st. congress isn't even in session. how is that possible?
.
trump: no, we're going to be passing -- no, no. we're putting in a resolution sometime in the next week, or week and a half, two weeks.
.
q: a resolution where?
.
trump: we're going to put in -- we're giving a middle-income tax reduction of about 10 percent. we're doing it now for middle-income people. this is not for business; this is for middle. that's on top of the tax decrease that we've already given them.
.
q: are you signing an executive order for that?
.
trump: no. no. no. i'm going through congress.
.
q: but congress isn't in session, though.
.
despite the fact that all of this was borderline incoherent -- i'm not sure what he thinks a "resolution" is -- the president repeated the vow at a rally in texas last night, boasting that the chairman of the house ways & means committee has been working on a new tax cut "for a few months," and the proposal is "going to be put in next week.".
.
none of this makes a lick of sense. no one in congress has any idea what this is about -- even white house officials are reportedly "mystified" -- and since capitol hill will be largely empty next week, there won't be anyone around to unveil a new multi-billion-dollar tax proposal.
#trumpliesabouteverything 
@realdonaldtrump

text:
dear men whoÂ are unusuallyÂ silent evenÂ after witnessing #metoo rise like a tsunamiÂ tide,

no.Â it's notÂ ok if you aren't speaking up. if you think these #metoo stories are just scandals, then you're making a biggest mistake in your life. 
just because you haven't harassed any woman,Â or you haven't seen anyone harassing, Â or you haven'tÂ heard of any such incidents, it doesn't mean that you aren't involvedÂ in this movement.Â all these years, #metoo stories continued and still continues because you weren't actuallyÂ involved and it wasn't openly discussed like now.

the outrageous storyÂ of every woman you hear now, is not just a story. it's a burden that remained rubbingÂ inside their heart folds. it's a rock ball that was stuck in their throat for years.Â it's a wound that's raw andÂ still bleeding. 
if you ask "why didn't womenÂ speak up publicly of these harassment storiesÂ before?" then, the answer is,Â because, may be,Â itÂ was considered too sensitive to beÂ discussed or may be, women had an unexplainable fear of being judged, or may be there wasn't space to express without any fear and insecurity.

but now, multiple women have come forward. they are speaking their heart out. butÂ will this take us to the desired future of "no more #metoo stories?" we can't say "definitely, yes," but to an extent, this canÂ make a difference, if you speak up.

you ask "how"? if you create a space in your home for your daughters and sons to openly discuss together about harassment, then, there can be a change. 
if you realize that each woman you meet in your lifeÂ has dealt with harassment and if you stand by them when they stand up for themselves, then,Â there can be a change.

if you have zero tolerance to abuse and speak out against theÂ men who abuse, then, there can be a change.

and if you understand whyÂ your mother is still afraid ofÂ her grand-daughter going out aloneÂ is not safe, then, there can be a change.

dear men reading this, be the change. 
break the silence. - charvi joy

christopoulos joined #theshecompassshow to talk about how she is using her voice and political position to ensure that all womenâ€™s voices, especially those that intersect race, class, and gender identity, are heard loud and clear. â€œfor me to speak my truth was the way that i found healing,â€ says christopoulos. â€œwhat i would say to survivors is that i believe you and itâ€™s not your fault. i stand with you and support you, and itâ€™s time that this becomes the new normal.â€ on continuing the fight for empowerment of all women and uplifting #intersectionalfeminism, christopoulos reminds us that â€œitâ€™s my job to hold the door open for another woman, to pass the baton on. i have always known what #whiteprivilege is and that i have it. if i donâ€™t hold the space for people of color and lgbtqia people, theyâ€™re not even in the picture. the most important thing you can do for a survivor is to believe them; i want to facilitate other survivors telling their story and shine a light to help others.â€ #watchnow (#linkinbio) as christopoulos shares her story and what sheâ€™s doing right now to ensure the voices of all women are loud and clear. available on #itunes #soundcloud and #spotify for #download on 10.26 #woc #womeninpodcasting #podcasting #podcast #tvshowhost #talkshow #host #womeninstem #womeninscience #femaleempowerment #metoo #swipeleft #anitahill #photo ğŸ“· @fmurphy & @instagram

text:
with the #metoo campaign currently going around, i feel like i need to share something. if you are a survivor of childhood sexual abuse, there is something you can do to help you on your journey to heal. 
the younique foundation offers a free retreat to survivors of childhood sexual abuse. they don't force younique products on you, they don't even use our products in the makeover and photoshoot because they don't want there to be even an ounce of room for someone to say they have the wrong intentions. this foundation has one purpose, and one purpose only: to help you heal. 
no business. no sales. nothing except opportunities for you to rediscover your self-worth and heal. you are powerful beyond measure. 
if you want to know more, please check out www.youniquefoundation.org, where you can read more and apply to attend the retreat or contact me. 
#nomore1in4 #reclaimhope  #ibelieveyou #morethenmakeup

text:
11:31 pm
feminists who changed the world - fanny wright 
the women who started the feminist revolution anticipated 'no small amount of misconception, misrepresentation, and ridicule'. and they got it. the first to speak out in public for women's rights in america - fanny wright, daughter of a scotch nobleman was called the 'red harlot of infidelity'. at every step of the way, the feminists had to fight the conception that they were violating the god-given nature of woman.

text:
i'm officially done being ashamed and scared about what i've been through. 
not just women, but everyone needs to be believed when it comes to the #metoo movement. 
sexual assault and rape, although very different, are both scarring and traumatic, and i think people see one as less than the other. yes, one is more serious and life altering. but sexual assault victims are still living through the trauma and flashbacks too. 
if you're a true friend and you remain friends with someone who's abused your friend, then you're not a friend. period. 
#timeforchange

text:
according to equality act 2010, the definition of sexual harassment includes indecent or suggestive remarks, unwanted touching, requests or demands for sex and the dissemination of pornography. 
however, this definition is insufficient and represents a gap in the uk legislation as it merely covers sexual harassment in the workplace. in addition, there is little grounds on enforcement as it relies on the victim to highlight the equality act to their manager and take their case to a tribunal.

text:
this weekend was one i will remember for a long while with fond memories. i generally try to live life with an open mind that leads to experiences that encourage me to think outside the box. this past saturday my friend jessica janniere @lookupandbeyond had the opportunity to speak about overcoming obstacles with women in the muslim community. as always jess was great and the connections made were and will continue to be impactful. during one of the ice breakers i had a moment to share some honest thoughts of what i thought about participating which was received well and the love in the room was felt. it is my personal belief that though we may not believe in the same manner without apology we can still show love to one another and glean from each otherâ€™s life experiences to become better overall. regardless of varying cultures and religion a lot of time we as women can relate to and help each other by communicating honestly and letting one know you are not alone . i made it and so can you!lğŸ’ªğŸ½
.
.

text:
a few months ago, i self-diagnosed that iâ€™m under some sort of depression. nothing in particular was the trigger. i just woke up one day feeling miserable and itâ€™s never changed ever since. to be 25 with no job at the same time no intention to be a burden to anyone, no savings, no assets, no progress in life, no capability to do anything for her family (yet they say), no â€˜potential romanceâ€™ and no idea when or how life is going to take a turn for the better but has bags of dreams, can be quite stressful. when i say self-diagnosed, i do not mean the kind that goes on exaggeration by just googling symptoms. i observed myself in every way possible. i tried my best, went for counselling sessions, woke up and jot down my first thought each morning, watched what i ate, noted how i felt at different times of the day and the result wasnâ€™t very favourable. i noticed how iâ€™ve changed from the pravina the world and i myself knew to the person i barely know now. for someone who is very expressive, i now find it hard to express myself even for the biggest of things. this is definitely not the person i was a few months ago, a year ago. and it doesnâ€™t feel right for the pravina i know to be in this body, living the â€˜ordinaryâ€™ life, with less laughter and more stress, less surprise and more isolation. i find solace in loneliness lately (which is very unlike me), and iâ€™m being asked why. to be very honest, i really donâ€™t know. but iâ€™m sorry. i have guilt written all over me. i truly apologise to everyone iâ€™m being cold to, iâ€™m not keeping in touch with, iâ€™m not responding as cheerfully to at the moment. and i appreciate every single person in my life who understands this and treats me with the same amount of love. iâ€™m forever indebted to this kindness iâ€™m showered with. |
depression doesnâ€™t have a face nor does it have a sign. when it comes it just comes. people say itâ€™s just a phase but i want to emphasize it not just a phase. it has the ability to break you completely for the rest of your life. so itâ€™s your call. do whatâ€™s necessary for you. if you canâ€™t come out of it immediately, take one step at a time. like me, for now just embrace what you are. #gwtb #notashamed #metoo

you are not sugar and spice and everything nice. you are strong, powerful, beautiful, bold, bright, funny, and loud. donâ€™t ever let anyoneâ€™s opinion of you become your truth, donâ€™t ever let anyone tell you you canâ€™t or itâ€™s impossible, donâ€™t let them treat you like less than or push you or your feelings aside. donâ€™t sit quietly on the side lines reap your reward. dance, sing, laugh, scream, cry, stomp, show up and show out. be kind, grateful, empathetic, strong and brave all at the same damn time. take your place in the world unapologetically and out loud. it is your time. we will pry the tight fist of the oppressors injustice open one finger at a time. no more #metoo, but #notme...notever. like the great rosa parks stand firm in your convictions and say nah!

text:
in the u.s., one in three women experience some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime. 51.1% of female victims of rape reported being raped by an intimate partner and 40.8% by an acquaintance. 91% of victims of rape and sexual assault are female, and nine percent are male. rape is the most under-reported crime; 63% of sexual assaults are not reported to police. the prevalence of false reporting is lowÂ â€”between 2% and 10%. for example, a study of eight u.s. communities, which included 2,059 cases of sexual assault, found a 7.1% rate of false reports. a study of 136 sexual assault cases in boston found a 5.9% rate of false reports. researchers studied 812 reports of sexual assault from 2000-2003 and found a 2.1% rate of false reports. (article from: https://www.nsvrc.org/statistics)

so when i say i believe her, i'm not saying no one ever lies. i'm saying, look at the statistics. this is something we are actively letting people get away with. we are a challenging and skeptical mass of people. i want a better world for my daughter. i hope she is never sexually assaulted. but heaven forbid it happens, i hope the future world won't accuse her of lying, or acting, or making it up. â¤ğŸ–¤ (link to the shirt in the bio)

text:
#metoo
i was just 12 years old. my 65 year old tutor used to touch me unappropriately during my classes. i couldn't utter a word in front of my parents as i was sure they wouldnt belive me because he had a great impression on my parents.
this is the very first time, i am sharing this incident with someone. i am still scared because i have this in my mind that nobody would ever believe me.
i have faced the similar incident one more time in my life and that too with a neighbour. then now i believe that most of times these henious things are done by the people whom we know from a long time and ones who are close to us.
i am still not comfortable with anyone's touch because many a times we dont know the difference between a good and a bad touch and its really important to make everyone aware about this stuff.
also, there are many other girls and women who face these kind of incidents in their own homes, workplaces and surroundings. i know nobody was there for me while this happened and i want to be or will be there standing for every person out there who goes through anything as such.

text:
dear good guysâ€¦
â€¦and i do believe there are more good guys than bad. 
we have loved you, cared for you and stood up for you. youâ€™re our brothers, fathers, husbands, lovers, and friends. but as every revelation of #metoo breaks through the country you get ever more defensive, looking for a chink in our armour. you may think that this has gone too far, but for us is just the beginning. even though weâ€™ve learnt to handle unwarranted advances, ignore stares and comments that make us feel stripped to the bone, our tolerance does not make a wrong right. 
you ask why we speak now and not then- yes, we had resigned ourselves to speak in whispers of deeds done in the dark. but for the first time but this movement has given us a chance to turn that whisper into a voice that can change the way weâ€™re treated. why wouldnâ€™t we take the chance? touching, teasing, puling, grabbing, pinching, stroking, leering, commenting or raping is not ok. it wouldnâ€™t be ok for you either. 
we women are strong. weâ€™ve had our reputations soiled based on the length of our skirts and the colour of our lipsticks. every one of us has a #metoo story, and despite these weâ€™ve still managed to shine. we donâ€™t need you to stand up for us. all we ask, is for you to believe.
- vasudha rai @vasudha.rai

text:
*the me too movement* post 2 . . 
when i started to post the stories about me too movement that all of you shared with me, i realised there are a lot of dads, husbands, brothers out there who also have their perspective on the matter. and it's only fair that we involve them in the discussions. 
so, i spoke to my so about the movement. one very important point that came out during the discussion about consent and how sometimes some men do not understand the meaning of no was that "it's sometimes very confusing for men. if the girl is smiling or blushing while saying no, we don't know what to make of it. can you girls please be strict and stern when you say a no so that men know that you mean it's a no." well, what my response to this was a different story altogether. but this made me think.... that may be there is a men's side of perspective that we sometimes are missing. so here, i'm asking all the men reading this. tell us, what's your take or advice on this movement. we might not agree to it, but we can definitely listen to your side too!!! . ğŸ“· @meinaalsharma

in life we experience extreme highs and at the same time we experience some pretty extreme lows.â£

â£
not recognizing that life has its ups and downs, that being defeated and making a comeback is just as important as moving forward because itâ€™s in those moments that youâ€™re thinking youâ€™ve hit the bottom, that youâ€™re only just beginning to cut yourself a new path in life.  you not being defeated youâ€™re being defined!â£
â£

â£

â£
dr. wayne dryer said it best, â€œwhen we change the way we look at things, the things we look at change.â€â£

text:
â€œearlier this year, the new york times ran a front-page story about the outrageous pensions being paid out to a few oregon retirees. the story, headlined â€œa $76,000 monthly pension: why states and cities are short on cash,â€ featured a former college football coach collecting more than $550,000 a year, and a retired university president pocketing $913,000. the story feeds into a popular myth that retired public-sector workers are getting fat and rich thanks to ordinary taxpayers, who are shouldering the costs of pensions so generous they have triggered a cascade of fiscal crises.

in reality, most retired public workers are living far more modestly. in 2014, the suburban chicago daily herald looked at nine statewide and local pensions, including those enjoyed by teachers, legislators, and university professors. the average pensioner, they found, received $32,000 a year. the illinois municipal retirement fund pays an average pension of only $22,284 a year, low enough for seniors to qualify for food stamps. most retired civil servants, moreover, donâ€™t receive social security. despite the rhetoric, public workers are generally paid less than their private-sector counterparts, even when factoring in benefits â€” 11 to 12 percent less, according to a 2010 analysis of two decades of data from the bureau of labor statistics.â€ .

text:
oh my sweet lord. i love a millions thing about this podcast, and have listened to it 4 times in the last 24 hours. the gender knot is created by my brilliant friend @nastarantavakolifar and this episode encapsulates a huge chunk of what i teach and coach my clients on. 
@realkasiaurbaniak the guest speaker nails it â€” she talks about how to get women to make powerful requests of men that are specific, and directive and how men can be with an empowered woman, especially at this time as the rage burns and the power of women increases. i believe that working together to shift the status quo is going to take us having conversations and taking action in ways weâ€™ve never done before. 
some highlights include what questions men are asking themselves right now in isolation and what conversation is needed to shift to bring men along as allies and collaborators as we collectively heal post - metoo. how women can make powerful requests of men with the full weight of their authority and how we are always training people in how to treat us. 
as women we need to learn to ask, invite and command men in what we need and want to shift the status quo. itâ€™s it certainly not easy, and takes some training. starting there is a huge triumph in my mind. knowing that we are worthy of asking.  as for the men, you can ask a lot of questions to the women in your life. a lot of questions. and you can ask a lot of questions of the men in your life. 
my fave line... â€œif a woman can break herself out of the patriarchal jail, and it would support her own freedom to go back in and save the men.â€ listen, and let me know what you think. podcast on itunes. #masculinefeminine #kasiaurbaniak #metoo #wakeup

text:
intro of myself; i'm whitney! 
like in my description i'm a mother, cosmetologist, an inspiring makeup artist, and a lover. one thing a lot of people don't know is that i'm a survivor. i grew up in an abusive home with parents who didn't properly take care of me or my siblings. i was sheltered from the world and didn't get to experience a lot of the things that people take granted of these days. i didn't go to school, i didn't even really have friends, but at the young age of 16, i decided it was enough. i worked my way through the heartache, the exhaustion, depression, the ptsd of my past. and, i love who i've become today. things may get hard, but i promise you it does get better! if for any reason you are feeling scared, alone, unstable or hurt. i will be there for you, i will be the moon that shines on you in your darkest hour. feel free to reach out to me, i am an open book and i will be there for you to the best of my abilities.

#survivor  #metoo #inspirationalquotes #bewhoyouwanttobe #advocate #itgetsbetter #darknessendsatsunrise

text:
everytime i start believing that sexual assault survivors are finally getting the support they deserve, people like these once again make me lose hope in humanity.
.
y'all simply don't realise how much courage and effort it takes to share your rape story - to recall the most triggering details of your assault and tell it to a bunch of skeptical men in a courtroom.
.
so many of you don't realise how hard it is to speak up in a society where rape culture is so very prevalent - where you're constantly shamed and blamed for things that aren't your fault.
.
it's hard to tell your story when you've got no "evidence", no support - sometimes even from your family, a sexist slut shaming society and a courtroom full of skeptical men to judge you. .
and yet victims get told that they're being "too dramatic". their courage is so often mistaken to be a grab for attention.
.
i thought that the #metoo movement would lead to more awareness about sexual assault. but really, nowadays the internet and newspapers are so full of it that people have started thinking it's some new internet trend.

text:
this psychologist has captured the core essence of the paradox for a survivor of abuse.

sharing oneâ€™s experience with another human being is the only way out of the abusive cycle. it is also the most painful.

while the external world may view â€œsharingâ€ through the lens of accusationsâ€¦pointing fingers, blaming, exploiting, and perhaps even totally  fabricating lies, that is not the lens the survivor wears.

the dsm-5 recognizes â€œnarcissistic personality disorderâ€ as a diagnosable mental disorder. the general public however, often does not recognize what is before them. but then, neither did the survivor in the beginning. 
the questions are always: â€œthen why did they wait so long?â€ â€œwhy were they silent?â€ â€œwhy did they stay?â€ â€œhow can they expect anyone to believe them when they said and did nothing all that time?â€ â€œhow did they not know what they were getting into?â€ #abuse isnâ€™t rational.

and thatâ€™s the probable answer....thatâ€™s the nature of covert psychological abuse. itâ€™s covert. that means even the victim doesnâ€™t realize whatâ€™s happening. itâ€™s not something anyone expects to encounter. particularly when youâ€™re in love. 
but the other answer is simply that, admitting such an experience isnâ€™t easy. 
it doesnâ€™t lend itself to bragging rights. itâ€™s probably not something anyone ever hoped they would be a part of. its never the answer to the age old childhood question â€œwhat do you want to do when you grow up? â€œ

who wants to be the one to admit they didnâ€™t have the balls to cope?  the courage to stand up? the strength to put all their fears aside? who wants to reveal that it was just easier to lie to themselves. attempt to hold things together for the sake of a family. pretend it wasnâ€™t happening. pretend everything was normal. wait for it to pass. hope. 
a hero they are not. 
this is not a club you want to join. 
there is no gold star, real or pretend, that is worth admitting one is a part of the survivors group. 
what there is, is pain. embarrassment.  humiliation. and, deep deep shame. 
if anyone manages to swallow all of that and share their experience, somebody somewhere needs to damn well believe them. #metoo

if you call yourself an advocate of human rights, you do not accept fgm of any kind for any reason.
it is should be the responsibility of each of us to condemn the act, show zero tolerance to fgm and stand in solidarity against the fight.

text:
#sabarimalareflections on #women #desires #thennow 
let me begin by saying, in recent history, there has never been a better time for us women in india, than now. 
we have everything we could imagine. 
roots, deep to give us the wisdom. and relationships - fathers, mothers, sisters, brothers, lovers, husbands, friends - warm, open minded, to give us the wings, the flight. 
we have the best of what our mothers, our grandmothers, even our great grand mothers, had. 
that said. there is nothing perfect. not here, not now, not ever. for if it were perfect, there would be no scope for growth. and to live, is to grow. - 
the above, and what follows, came to me very strongly as i was meditating this morning. and, even as i had been resisting, i could not stop myself from sharing this anymore. much as i know it will make all of us with modern conditionings uncomfortable, i just have to say it. 
so, with gentle apologies for the discomfort my words might cause, i begin. - 
in india we have heard the numbers â€œ10-50 age group womenâ€ repeatedly over the past few weeks. on television, on social media, on newspapers, in conversations. ten to fifty women. and said, almost in the same breath is the word â€œmenstruationâ€, followed by â€œimpurityâ€. the age group 10-50 of women not being allowed into sabarimala, has nothing to do with menstural impurity. that has been said. 
but what i intuitively sense is, that it has nothing to do with menstruation as well. 
it has to do with that deeper process that makes a woman release the old tissues. prepare her womb with a new warmth. release her invitation in the form of ovum, in an awaiting of what is the greatest act of creativity on this earth, a child. 
this whole issue is at its very basis a struggle between two thought patterns - one ancient indian, other modern western -  concerning the most basic human desire #sex. 
how #ancientindians have seen, lived it. 
and how, #modernwestern mind perceives it, lives it. â€” 
#precolonialindia #womenssexuality 
i invite you to go back. imagine. 
from what we know, this shrine of ayyappa and the sadhana traditions were set up in 1100s. ğŸ‘‡

text:
someone once told me that no matter what everyone has their own agenda. i didn't want to understand at the time because i was blinded by my own negative thoughts and was too upset to care. but, now i know what that means. i realized that no matter what the people around us will never want the same things we do, will never think like us, will never mature at our pace, will never fully understand why we do what we do, will never see things the way we do. it's not a bad thing, it's just how life works. we are constantly trying to change others and getting upset when they don't because of this same thing. their priorities are different from ours. the things that are truly fulfilling to them might be fun to us but it won't make us happy. it's very important to understand this and choose to be around the people that maybe won't have your same priorities but are understanding of this and are willing to respect and let you do what's best for you. life is about being happy and sharing that happiness with someone who's priorities are as important as your own. ğŸğŸ‘‘ğŸ’
.

text:
a televised rape trial in south africa has prompted a furious public backlash after a witness - who says she was raped by her pastor from the age of 14 - was subjected to a lengthy and, at times, aggressively intimate cross-examination by the lawyer representing a 60-year-old nigerian televangelist, timothy omotoso, who denies the allegation.

over the weekend, mr omotoso's church, in the coastal city of port elizabeth, was forced to shut its door after angry crowds besieged the building, while a sunday newspaper reported that the woman who gave evidence against him - cheryl zondi, now a 22-year-old student - had received death threats ahead of the trial.
the trial - the first prominent rape case to be broadcast live in a country where more than 100 rapes are reported to the police each day - has attracted huge interest, and raised difficult questions about victims' rights, impartiality and whether justice is best served by having television cameras in courtrooms.

anti-apartheid icon nelson mandela's granddaughter, ndileka mandela - who said in 2017 that she had been raped by a former boyfriend - is one of many south african women who have voiced support for ms zondi, linking her experience to the global #metoo movement. ğŸ“¸#gettyimagessoweto

use this link: https://shareanonymous.org/share-your-story/ you are not alone. 
you're also invited to participate in our ongoing project which seeks to curate data on sexual violence in nigeria.

text:
.
'voice of a woman' by bhavana varun
.
.
voiceless..they never were 
it's just that they were suppressed 
by a fear..by a feeling of disgust 
that why it happens to them 
how..did they become so numb
.
when and what..did they do
to end up in such a situation
and where will it finally end 
the truth, my dear women is 
we've all gone through 
the pain at some point .
.
while few among us muster courage 
to knock down these 
monsters in human forms 
the others find it difficult to accept 
why oh! why did it happen to them
.
think of these demons in our own homes
think of these psychopaths 
in your neighbourhoods
does it bring peace ever to your mind? 
do you still get sleep 
can you call it sound? 
i have walked through 
the roads of girlhood once .
.
yet when i think of all the little girls 
in my village and the nearby town 
i still stumble upon 
the same suffocating question 
should i be frightened or should i frown .
.
what do you call a fear 
when it is the life that you live. .
'how do you define those moments 
that make your life look like a scariest dream'
when your once happiest dream 
turn into your worst nightmares?
not all have the strength to 
break these shackles .
.

the same fear trickles down my nerves 
when i think of all the little girls 
i don't know when we'll have a civilised world
will we have it or not we are still unaware 
world, not of predators 
preying on innocent souls .
but i do dream of a world 
that doesn't defame her, assault her 
or brings down her morale 
but a world where men hold women's hand 
in solidarity and support .
.
'voice of a woman' by bhavana varun 
#metoo .
.

'voice of a woman' by bhavana varun
.
.
voiceless..they never were 
it is just that they were suppressed 
by a fear..by a feeling of disgust 
that why it happens to them 
how..did they become so numb
.
when and what..did they do
to end up in such a situation
and where will it finally end 
the truth, my dear women is 
we've all gone through 
the pain at some point .
.
while few among us muster courage 
to knock down these 
monsters in human forms 
the others find it difficult to accept 
why oh! why did it happen to them
.
think of these demons in our own homes
think of these psychopaths 
in your neighbourhoods
does it bring peace ever to your mind? 
do you still get sleep 
can you call it sound? 
i have walked through 
the roads of girlhood once .
.
yet when i think of all the little girls 
in my village and the nearby town 
i still stumble upon 
the same suffocating question 
should i be frightened or should i frown .
.
what do you call a fear 
when it is the life that you live. .
'how do you define those moments 
that make your life look like a scariest dream'
when your once happiest dream 
turn into your worst nightmares?
not all have the strength to 
break these shackles .
.

the same fear trickles down my nerves 
when i think of all the little girls 
i do not know when we'll have a civilised world
will we have it or not we are still unaware 
world, not of predators 
preying on innocent souls .
but i do dream of a world 
that does not defame her, assault her 
or brings down her morale 
but a world where men hold women's hand 
in solidarity and support .
.
'voice of a woman' by bhavana varun 
#metoo .
.

text:
survivors often ask me: did you ever think you would find love after your assault? 
answer: thatâ€™s tricky. â¬‡ï¸
.
.
 i was in love when my assault happened. but assault changes you. it changed the relationship i was in. we outgrew each other. so i wasnâ€™t sure finding it again was an option. .
.
i dated someone after i ended the above relationship. he taught me so much about the value i brought to a relationship and showed me i deserved to be placed first in someoneâ€™s life. he helped me forget about what happened to me. .
.
i wasnâ€™t prepared for love when @chris_shade came along. but i knew he was different. his charisma, style, sense of purpose, dry humor, knowledge of his self worth. he has helped me process, accept, and grow from my assault- because he loves the woman i am. .
.
so did i think i would find love, no. did i, absolutely. it gets easier, survivors. you just have to keep believing in the power of love, good humans, and looking for someone who accepts you as you are and is ready to challenge you to be better. â¤ï¸

text:
i'm so proud to be a woman.. a #phenomenalwoman.. i believe i'm a divine intervention of maa dugga..the creator,the warrior, the mother all at the same time.. the kind of pressure we handle in our society and work places collectively, can be amusing to others.. but still we got it all.. there are situations where some of us may feel intimidated and even scared.. some of us became numb and buries the torture or pain in our hearts.. and this is the #moment for us ladies to truly #speakup .. no time to be hesitant .. we need to collectively change the scenario for the betterment of our society and for a better work environment.. the #metoo #movement #2018 #india has given us a platform to say it out loud.. although there are still that age-old patriarchal #sexism exists in our beliefs but dear women please know it will be demolished gradually as we speak up and make a stand for ourselves.. let's make it through; #together .. more power to #us

text_retweet:
#repost @bigworldbreaks ... #repost @nikkitaoliver ...
dear community -
it is time to register for the seattle black panther party youth empowerment summit (y.e.s.).
â¡ when? the summit is saturday, november 10th, 2018.
â¡ time? 9am-5pm
â¡ where? rainier beach high school
â¡ for whom? youth 13-24
â¡ free! breakfast & lunch provided.
â¡ why y.e.s.? this past spring the seattle bpp celebrated its 50th anniversary. they commemorated this momentous occasion with a 3-day summit highlighting the legacy of the bpp and how the work has continued. many attended the event and were inspired by the stories, workshops and relationship building.
â¡ so whatâ€™s next? the bpp of seattle knows that the youth are not simply our future leaders, but they are our present day leaders and revolutionaries. the average age in the bpp was 19 years old. they were on the frontlines of much needed social change. it is essential we recognize that the same is true today. young people are on the frontlines of the most dynamic social justice movements: #blacklivesmatter, climate change, #metoo, gun violence, #nonewyouthjail, etc. youth empowerment summit (y.e.s.) is a way of continuing the 50th anniversary and fulfilling our mission to empower our community in the discussion of action and strategies to address the issues we are facing.
(registration link in bio - please share with the youth in your life)

text:
"sunsets are proof that no matter what happens, every day can end beautifully"-kristen butler. ğŸŒ…

throwback to the most beautiful sunset i ever laid eyes on, so beautiful it brought tears to my eyes. on a boat, right in the middle of the eastern pacific ocean, with a small cabbin crew and a group of wonderful individuals (including my fave @andreaksingh ğŸ’—) exploring the galapagos islands no other machine or human being in sight. absolute perfection.

i've had some pretty awful flashbacks and night terrors recently after finally building up the courage to confront the person responsible for my ptsd for his actions. unfortunately there was no acknowledgement, no apology and therefore no closure. the response i recieved was just a series of classic minimising, gaslighting and derailing tactics that i have actually become an expert in recognising after many years of working with surviviors of domestic violence and sexual abuse. unsuprising and predictable, but still so harmfull. 
i'm proud of myself for speaking my truth and have had to come to the realisation that i will never get closure from this person, because he will never own his shit or take responsibility for his abusive behaviour. 
on that note, remembering i have lived through moments like the one captured in this photograph are a beacon of happiness and hope for me in times where the lowest moments i have lived through creep up and consume me, along with everyone and everything around me. i have seen so much beauty in this world, sometimes when i think about all the phenomenonal things i have seen and done and all the things i am going to see and do i almost need to pinch myself because there have been so many times when life has been anything but beautiful. i can't believe how ugly and beautiful life can be at the same time. .
.
.

text: predators are masters of illusion. they enmesh themselves into the fabric of the lives of others in a way that keeps their true nature completely hidden. so much so, a lot of people will passionately defend their character or intentions while casting doubt on the victim. after all, when someone is doing something so noble as coaching, teaching, healing, or spiritually guiding, they must be good people with honorable intentions, right? wrong!!!! parents need to watch out for these people with the same fervor that they employ when it comes to strangers. this aau coach, like so many other predators, abuse kids for years because parents, caregivers and other adults never perceive them as a threat because the predator presents as a nice, caring person with good intentions. be on guard; they are among us.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

#repost @nikkitaoliver ...
dear community -
it is time to register for the seattle black panther party youth empowerment summit (y.e.s.).
â¡ when? the summit is saturday, november 10th, 2018.
â¡ time? 9am-5pm
â¡ where? rainier beach high school
â¡ for whom? youth 13-24
â¡ free! breakfast & lunch provided.
â¡ why y.e.s.? this past spring the seattle bpp celebrated its 50th anniversary. they commemorated this momentous occasion with a 3-day summit highlighting the legacy of the bpp and how the work has continued. many attended the event and were inspired by the stories, workshops and relationship building.
â¡ so whatâ€™s next? the bpp of seattle knows that the youth are not simply our future leaders, but they are our present day leaders and revolutionaries. the average age in the bpp was 19 years old. they were on the frontlines of much needed social change. it is essential we recognize that the same is true today. young people are on the frontlines of the most dynamic social justice movements: #blacklivesmatter, climate change, #metoo, gun violence, #nonewyouthjail, etc. youth empowerment summit (y.e.s.) is a way of continuing the 50th anniversary and fulfilling our mission to empower our community in the discussion of action and strategies to address the issues we are facing.
(registration link in bio - please share with the youth in your life)

dear good guys,
the silence from you is being noticed. 
bro code, bromance, bros before hoes - and all the other fragile walls of bro-fence you're hiding behind is being noticed. you saw, you knew, you know. why this silence then? you never missed an opportunity to share your entitled opinions before. 
because, how could you fail a bro? it's his "private matter", better not to be involved? society never taught you men to talk about personal responsibilities in the first place? which excuse are we going with today, #deargoodguys?
you are better than this. we are better than this. we can do better than this. 
let's talk.
-opashona ghosh @opashona .

itâ€™s been eight years since south korean prosecutor seo ji-hyun says she was sexually harassed, but itâ€™s still painful to recall. â€œfor a long time, i tortured myself by blaming myself for everything,â€ she tells time in seoul. seo alleges she was repeatedly groped at a funeral by a senior male colleague, while the countryâ€™s justice minister sat nearby, in 2010. seo reported the incident to her managers shortly after, but was subjected to performance audits that she describes as unfair, and assigned to a lower level branch outside seoulâ€”a move she says did not match her strong track record at work. last fall, seo watched as #metoo took off. she began to grasp how widespread sexual harassment and assault were. seo added her voice to the rising global chorus in january, sharing her experience in an open letter on her workplace intranet and signing it with #metoo. within a few hours of posting, she says the justice department said her statement was false and refused to issue an apology. (the ministry of justice did not respond to timeâ€™s repeated requests for comment on the case; seoâ€™s alleged harasser has denied the charge, saying he was too drunk at the time to recall what happened.) that evening, seo spoke on one of south koreaâ€™s most influential news programs. her words resonated: she is widely credited with kick-starting south koreaâ€™s version of the movement. womenâ€™s rights activists and survivors across asia have seen the global reckoning confronting sexual harassment, assault and abuse as a chance to shape their own national conversations about gender #inequality, amid intense backlash and great personal risk. but the broader cultural impact of speaking out in such challenging environments is creating a groundswell of support and solidarity. photograph by @timfranco for time. video by @ariahychen for time

text: "from rebecca traister, the new york times bestselling author of all the single ladies--whom anne lamott called "the most brilliant voice on feminism in this country"--comes a vital, incisive exploration into the transformative power of female anger and its ability to transcend into a political movement. in the year 2018, it seems as if women's anger has suddenly erupted into the public conversation. but long before pantsuit nation, before the women's march, and before the #metoo movement, women's anger was not only politically catalytic--but politically problematic. the story of female fury and its cultural significance demonstrates the long history of bitter resentment that has enshrouded women's slow rise to political power in america, as well as the ways that anger is received when it comes from women as opposed to when it comes from men"--

i find the #metoo movement to be triggering as fuck. iâ€™m in awe of its power, but itâ€™s both absolutely necessary for our society and extremely painful, in equal measures. on one hand, iâ€™m grateful for the cleansing power of the truth, and iâ€™m inspired by the strength it takes my fellow survivors to gaze upon the the truth, especially in front of other people and especially when theyâ€™re directly confronting those who have harmed them. but on the other hand, reading/hearing about the trauma of others makes me miserable because it forces me to gaze upon my own truth which leads to a self-hate landslide from which recovery can feel impossible. and as much as i anticipate coming to terms with â€˜the things i hate thinking aboutâ€™ when iâ€™m meditating or practicing yoga, iâ€™m much less prepared to deal with my baggage when iâ€™m innocently scrolling through social media feeds.

when i watched dr. fordâ€™s testimony, all i could think was â€œi canâ€™t believe sheâ€™s brave enough to talk about this in front of other people.â€ i was in awe. spellbound. talking about it on the international stage must be like living a nightmare. i wouldnâ€™t know, as i canâ€™t bring myself to do the same because my memories both horrify and embarrass me. and iâ€™m well aware that i need not be embarrassed but that doesnâ€™t make the emotions any less real.

iâ€™m fascinated by the ways in which we all view/experience/hold our trauma. i wish sensitivity and empathy were considered as valuable as anger. surviving is more than just fodder for content. 
#ibelieveher #yoga

fact: it is a crime to have sex with a person who cannot consent due to being intoxicated or drugged. remember that drinking and taking drugs does not influence good decision making.

in the spirit of supporting survivors of sexual violence, we are also shutting down rape myths. survivors deserve to be heard. safe. believed.

text:

@akash_adhikari_______  #metoonepal

this is the video of the official statement released even as more and more heads are rolling, and skeletons are tumbling out of a closet that is many years old in the wake of #metoo storm in india and hollywood. â€œthe nepali film producersâ€™ associations is committed to work towards making workplaces in the industry safe spaces for everyone. in this regard, chairman mr. akash adhikari has unveiled an official video and addressing about the issue of sexual harassment at the workplace within the industry. "we are determined to stay the course till workplaces in the industry are safe spaces for everyone", he said in video. 
he also urged to start to implement robust processes in their workplaces to ensure the highest standards of safety for employers and crew members, whether in offices or on the sets of productions. 
meanwhile, taking to the micro-blogging site, twitter and facebook, documentary film maker and hollywood's emmy award nominated subina shrestha has accused unnamed minister of sexual misconduct at workplace.

text:
on the #internationalchefsday i was invited by the staff at @hyattregencyahmedabad to sample the delights of their dimsum fest and what a treat it was! i was floored by the presentation and most importantly the taste. you know the efforts put into a dish when you eat it. you most certainly do! and that's what i experienced yesterday. you might feel a degree of hyperbole in the words but believe you me, there is none. the food there was simply delicious. the fest is on till the 31st of this month and if you are anything like me when it comes to food, you would not want to miss out on this one. .
.
.

text:
bullying and harassing people isn't new, especially on social networking sites. though there is cyber cell and everything that takes effective measures to deal with these things but what about the mental state of the victim? what about the trauma that the victim is left with during the whole time? this is one incident where i felt the urge to talk about and do something on my behalf. as this isn't a new thing and most of us go through it, it does not even get the attention and exposure that it should be getting. this person has stooped ways down to humiliate a girl who did not pay him much heed and after doing all this, his instagram account is still active and he's still there without any guilt. please report this person and spread the word. 
full story- theprototypicalindian.wordpress.com 
link in bio.
.
.

a â€˜pointingâ€™ masterclass from jack lowden & hayley atwell after discussing the new measure for measure at donmar warehouse. in josie rourkeâ€™s production, shakespeareâ€™s play about sex, power & exploitation is offered twice: in the first half - set in 1604 - angelo abuses his bequeathed power to exploit the chaste & pious isabella. after the interval weâ€™re in 2018, powerful isabella is a sexual predator & angelo is now her victim. a #metoo m4m? strangely, the 1604 version seems more pertinent to whatâ€™s happening in 2018 than the contemporary role reversal of act 2. maybe a single measure would suffice, but brilliantly played by both in a bold & thought-provoking production nonetheless. listen to our interview on front row, wednesday.

text:
sisterhood is coming to glastonbury!
12th nov, 7.30pm @ assembly rooms

groundbreaking work â€œat its core sisterhood is a superbly written, intelligent, and essential play, masterfully portrayed by its three actresses, exploring the role of male domination, misinformation, sexual abuse, and age discrimination through the lens of the past but contrasted with moments drawn from the modern day.â€ - fringe review

like hand maids tale, but with more hope, sisterhood is a gentle but fearless adventure into the dark heart of patriarchal rule. three women, aged 20, 40 and 60 (but not a virgin, mother or hag in sight) stand on a precipice, the patriarchy watching over them â€“ flaming torches aloft â€“ threatening to burn them all.

sisterhood is a newly devised multimedia tale introducing you to a sisterhood caught between two timelines: the witch trials of the 16thc and modern-day women facing a world in political and environmental upheaval. sisterhood transports the audience, in this extra-live performance, to a church cell in wilmington, where three women await their trial in the morning. soothing and passionate storytelling interweaves the stories of these three women with vestiges from the performers own lives, to reveal an immediate and clear association. text: i opened my heart up about my ptsd today to my aunt. how it's affected me. my traumas. i need to talk about one today. i went to nepal last year for university and so much happened. before going to nepal, i had already been diagnosed with ptsd, but this trauma has just ruined me. one weekend in nepal, i went to travel to pokhara and i was caught in the middle of a landslide. people died, including police officers trying to save us. after being trapped for 20 hours with very little to eat and drink, we were free and i arrived at my hotel in the early morning the next day. because i was only in pokhara for a day, i went on an organised tour. i met some people on that tour and later that night, was drugged and raped by one of them. it was a weekend of hell. i was lucky though. on the bus home, there was a woman on the bus who could tell that i wasn't okay. she got me to open up about what had happened. it turned out that she was a nurse. she took me to a hotel, she changed her flights home to take me to hospital, she looked after me. she cried with me. she was there for me.  i was treated and tested for every std under the sun, including hiv/aids. i got very sick from it. luckily, even though i was treated for everything, i had no std's. in summary, it was a very fucked weekend. and i re-live this memory often. in fact, i am uncontrollably trembling right now as i write about it. there is so much more of this story that i could go into but this is hard. and it's confronting. over a year later, i am still dealing with stuff like this on the daily. what happened to me was not okay. i am getting stronger and stronger every day at handling it all. these things need to be talked about. it needs to be recognised that this is a problem. women need to be heard.

text:
finally finished 5/10 days of the #10x10challenge where we run 10 kms back to back for 10 days. it has been such a powerful journey not just for my body and the mind. taking every day at a time is a hard when you know your goal is so far fetched. so what i do is take it every run as if it were my last. giving it my all. i am feeling a change in my form, groove and breathing significantly from day 1 to now. mentally, i have calmed down a lot. since coming out in the #metoo campaign my moods have been all over the place. i was not able to get out of bed and was feeling super low on energy. the last 5 days have brought back my focus to the only thing i can control and change - the self. iâ€™m also less angsty at work and am able to be patient with co workers. super excited to finish the challenge in the next 5 days. special shout out to @mumbairunners @bombayrunning @deepakoberoi for orchestrating this. you really are changing lives ! â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

text:
my mom is a constant source of strength. she showed me by example that women, regardless of how difficult life may get, can do it all.

this is what iâ€™ve experienced everyday. 
i move out of the bus, another girl moves out beside me, now she walks ahead of me wondering if iâ€™m following her, whilst iâ€™m just taking a normal route on my way back home. i try sprinting so that i could cross her, wondering whether that would make her feel comfortable, but she rushes with fear in her eyes getting a sense of assurance with every step that i am definitely following her. this is what we have created, this is what we have done to the world. we have created such an environment today that no girl feels safe walking in her own neighbourhood, no women would leave the bus without watching backwards, no women can walk for few meters without wondering if someone is following her. so what do i do? i stop walking, i pretend that iâ€™m texting someone or either i cross the road and walk on the other side to make sure that, that particular girl feels safe while walking back home.iâ€™m so proud of that girl because she left her home and does what she has to even while being completely aware about what is out there and i did what i could do to make her feel safe. maybe i did a good work there but what am i doing while there are endless numbers of women, who regardless of this worldâ€™s cruelty are still fighting, who wants to scream every night before they go to sleep, who are stumbling, who are trying, who want to give up, who are seeking for help, who just requires one person to listen to them. let us be your voices, let us be your screams. this is to every woman, who i have known , who i have met or whoever is reading this. i believe in you â¤
i know this wonâ€™t take away the pain or memories of what youâ€™ve been through, nor would it make it any easier but it is just my way of saying that i believe in you and i am there with you â¤ .

text:
the rwandan school turning boys into feminists.in a village outside rwanda's capital kigali, a group of boys are learning how to stop gender-based violence and the power imbalances in the #metoo era.

while girls learn about investment to achieve financial independence, the boys are taught how to report abuse and how to respect the girls and women in their lives in a classroom next door.

these sessions take place after official academic classes are finished for the pupils at the safe school for girls, which is co-educational.

each weekday afternoon the boys and girls split up to learn different ways to improve the lives of women across rwanda. "if we happen to see such violence, we report them and make sure the people who have [committed the violence] are judged," rini mutijima, an 18-year-old at the school spoke.
name: BBFela
tweet_full:
the rwandan school turning boys into feminists.in a village outside rwanda's capital kigali, a group of boys are learning how to stop gender-based violence and the power imbalances in the #metoo era.

while girls learn about investment to achieve ficial independence, the boys are taught how to report abuse and how to respect the girls and women in their lives in a classroom next door.

these sessions take place after official academic classes are finished for the pupils at the safe school for girls, which is co-educational.

each weekday afternoon the boys and girls split up to learn different ways to improve the lives of women across rwanda. "if we happen to see such violence, we report them and make sure the people who have [committed the violence] are judged," rini mutijima, an 18-year-old at the school spoke.

text:
we have been told since our childhood that "milk" is an excellent nutritional supplement and is the best for your health, body and mind but is the "milk" that we drink today really the elixir we think of or is it a "slow poison" that can jeopardize entire generation of indians.

the debate here is are we drinking the milk we ought to be drinking? did the "white revolution", which we are so proud of, really gave us the enormous quantity of milk which ought to be given to us?

and this is where it boils down to species of milk that most of us might not know and that is a1 milk and a2 milk.

a1 milk vs. a2 milk

the difference between a1 milk and a2 milk is that one is formed with a1 protein and the other a2 protein. these a1 and a2 protein are different types of beta-casein proteins which form a large chunk of proteins present in milk. 
so how does consumption of a1 milk differs from a2 milk?

in simple words one type of milk is the elixir that i mentioned and the other type of milk is the poison that i mentioned.

the a2 milk is the "best thing" your body can have while a1 milk is a "basket of diseases". a1 milk has been related to autism, diabetes, indigestion and even schizophrenia. the a1 protein releases bcm -7 which is an opioid(a substance that affects the nervous system). therefore it is the a2 milk that needs to be consumed and not a1 milk.

to read further.... https://www.facebook.com/milkawareness .
.

.

be it sexual or social. its very easy to make life a living hell for anyone in our "modern" society. 
i've always wondered though who the real bully is.....
-the accused ?
or the society which discriminates the victim? which incriminates them and denies them the right to a normal life.. who is the bully? and who is the victim here?

text:
@regran_ed from @thedailyember -  let me make it clear: there is no, none, zip, zero, working class party in america that can currently save us from the two corporate parties running us dry while the 1% collect the money from our work. iâ€™ve been reading chris hedges book â€œdeath of the liberal class,â€ and itâ€™s really made me look at our current situation. we have two wall street parties, two pro war parties, two pro-fossil fuel parties (like it or not the dems are barely any better, they flipped on taking donations from the fossil fuel industry within a month of pledging not to.) we have two parties that work in the interest of the few while the many suffer to get by. iâ€™m not calling for violence but iâ€™m saying that we cannot continue down this path of allowing small incremental changes to be enough. we need radical change that will benefit the masses and not just the few.
.
.

text:
in a timely, upcoming book, author sohaila abdulali  who was gang-raped as a teenager and was among the first survivors to speak out about rape back in the 1980s -- draws on three decades of grappling with the issue. "what we talk about when we talk about rape" coincides with the rising tide of the #metoo campaign in india.

in the book, abdulali, who has previously authored two novels as well as children's books and short stories, mentions that she faced "deafening silence" on rape in india for over three decades, but contends that the discourse around it changed after the 2012 nirbhaya rape case in delhi.

she contended that #metoo is "a great start" but "it's certainly not going to end sexual violence". "we need systematic change, in legislation, in attitudes, in our basic belief structures, for us to really decide as a society that men actually don't have the right to abuse women.the hinterlands are filled with tough women who have always dealt with issues of sexual violence, often in very creative ways. i don't think we need to assume that urban women have answers they don't, and that it is a one-way street. i think women in all strata of society have much to learn from each other," said abdulali, who has an ma in communication from stanford university.

she wrote an article in a woman's magazine questioning how we perceive rape and rape victims. the story went viral 30 years later, in the wake of the 2012 delhi rape case and the global outcry that followed.

text:
#metoo - post 3
.
in my last two posts, i talked about why many victims donâ€™t speak up & how there is no shame in that. there is shame in shaming the victims & unfortunately, thatâ€™s a tragic reality even today. we need a major revamp in mentality.
.
i got tons of dms & comments from women here who mentioned their stories. many said they still donâ€™t have the courage to talk about it openly but maybe one day, they will.
.
hereâ€™s what i wanna say - not being able to speak about it openly is not a sign of weakness!â¤ï¸
.
itâ€™s a personal choice & your reasons donâ€™t have to be justified to anyone. i have no reason for not speaking up earlier. iâ€™m also not ashamed that i didnâ€™t because only i know how i felt then & that is true for all of us. the only people who should feel ashamed are the pricks who molested/hassled/assaulted someone.
.
unfortunate fact is that molestation or sexually exploitation in some form or the other is very prevalent in india & a change is desperately needed. however, despite suffering from such a traumatic experience, majority of the victims (women/men/girls/boys) continue to carry on with their lives.
.
they go to school, college or work everyday. they travel in buses, autos or cars day & night. they do grocery shopping or buy clothes & shoes. they meet their friends for coffee or drinks. they take care of their families, kids & households.ğŸ™Œ
.
if that is not courage, then i donâ€™t know what is!â¤ï¸
.
so regardless of whether you shared your story publicly or not, remember that over time, you did not let it break you! ğŸ’ª
.
the fact that you continue to live your life everyday makes you strong! and that is something to be proud of! ğŸ¤—

text:
after almost a year the #metoo movement which stunned the west and european countries, is finally making its presence felt in india. most of us won't be surprised to see the number of stories that has been breaking out. everyday we read and watch news relating to sexual assaults and harassment, but it has become more a 4 line story or a 10 second news.

these stories are being heard now because many well respected personalities are telling their heart wrenching stories collectively.
that's the strength and impact of this movement, making people to come out in numbers.honestly it's a slap to our societal order. more to our over protective, holier than thou, 'sanskari' and 'log kya kahenge' attitude.

leave aside the movement, freedom of speech and expression is apparently a constitutional right, still most can't voice theirs concerns over these issues because of so called family values.talking about sex and issues relating to it is still a taboo in most parts of the nation. even if someone tries to be brave enough to tell their story, our judiciary and mostly family makes a mockery of it.

somehow harassment victim become an untouchable and laughable as it is, victims are asked to keep mum while the culprits walk freely probably with increased confidence of doing the same thing over and over.'sanskar' being the heart of our culture, some would rather watch someone's dignity shred to pieces, than to take a 'kalank' on their 'daaman'. this movement is an eye opener for such people.the guilty should be answerable for their actions, it shouldn't be the other way around.

#metoo #metooindia #against #sexualcrime #harassment #workplace #life #inspiration #movement #india #respct

text:
the full version is on youtube (link in bio). as many of you know, and many more of you donâ€™t, iâ€™ve been going through a pretty tough time these past few months (or honestly, the past 12 years). from the age of 14 to 16, i was the victim of ongoing sexual assault and rape by a person i trusted, who was in a position where they were meant to protect me, and instead they abused that power. i didnâ€™t tell anyone, i kept this secret to myself. as much as i wanted to tell someone, i couldnâ€™t. this year i finally thought iâ€™d accepted it, and i came forward to the police with what had happened to help them with an investigation to put my abuser away. i believed i was the only victim, and it turns out i wasnâ€™t. after coming forward, i was suddenly under the realisation i wasnâ€™t okay, and that i needed help.

i wrote this song for me. itâ€™s my story, my journey. it has helped empower me, find strength, and accept what happened. i am so proud of myself, because this was a huge step forward in my recovery, and every time i sing this song, i feel a bit stronger. he has no power over me anymore.

it is 2018 and there are still people questioning and blaming the victims of sexual assault. there are people openly excusing the crimes being committed. and every time somebody does that, it makes it even harder for another victim to come forward with their story. i was terrified to come forward because i was scared of what people would think, but now i know i didnâ€™t need to be. i was supported by my family and friends from day one. not everybody is as lucky as that in these situations, but i assure you that you will get the support you need. i know iâ€™m not alone anymore, and neither will you. 
i am not defined by what he did to me, i am me.

text:
locked...
.
for how long she laid 
she knew no more 
in the garage, which was
once her solace 
now her hell
.
she tried to move 
but the pain was so great
she sobbed again
.
gathering all her strenght
she tried to sit up
the happenings of the day
still jumbled her thoughts
.
the head still hurting
and with the blurry eyes 
she looked down 
and saw the blood
running down her thigh
she held her head 
and wailed so high
.
all they did 
was laugh and boom
locked her inside 
in a world of her own
.
-a lady in black
 veil

text:
after getting my shoes fixed, i now have close to 30 pairs of shoes to wear. problem is, i only have one pair of feet #firstworldproblem and i've sold the shelf for my shoes thinking i'll be moving out but i didn't. ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘ˆ .

to cut the story short, i guess all things happened for a good reason. without a shoes shelf, i won't be adding on new shoes that's for sure. and i can then properly downsize my existing shoes collection. these are all old soles #punintended and i think i still have a lot of shoes from a minimalist wannabe perspective. .

imagine i had way more than this few years before i moved to malaysia (end 2015) and when i started downsizing my life in 2014. and i am still at it! it's been such a slow process and it definitely took way longer than it should. i wonder why does it took so long? either i have way too much stuff or i just can't bear to let go. i believe it's both. i have stuffs from aeons ago and i still want to wear them. they still make me happy or in marie kondo's words - they still 'spark joy' - they all do! ğŸ™ƒğŸ™ƒğŸ™ƒ .

a friend recommend another book call 'goodbye, things'. i hope to get some enlightenment from there on how to go minimal. i don't have much time left. it's almost the end of 2018!!
.
.
.
#myzerowastejourney

womenâ€™s experiences with rape and assault are real, and when they speak up about it, we should listen and be worried and upset.

food for thought:
don't know when it became socially acceptable for people to start conversations by commenting on weight gain or loss. being in my industry, i get comments all the time about my weight (not saying that's ok either). it's almost like a greeting. however, yesterday, i witnessed an "auntie" commenting on a little kid (around 10 years old) on how fat he was and how big is belly is (and then proceed to touch is belly and cheeks). since when was that a kind gesture or a cute hello? it can be damaging to a kid's self esteem in so many ways. i immediately endeavored to rescue a bit of the kid's shattered dignity by complimenting him on how athletic he was (he was jumping around before). there are better conversation starters than that. shoutout to all of you who have been emotionally abused like that before! stay strong! their opinions don't matter. smile on! ğŸ’ª
.
.
.

food for thought:
do not know when it became socially acceptable for people to sta conversations by commenting on weight gain or loss. being in my industry, i get comments all the time about my weight (not saying that's ok either). it is almost like a greeting. however, yesterday, i witnessed an "auntie" commenting on a little kid (around 10 years old) on how fat he was and how big is belly is (and then proceed to touch is belly and cheeks). since when was that a kind gesture or a cute hello? it can be damaging to a kid's self esteem in so many ways. i immediately endeavored to rescue a bit of the kid's shattered dignity by complimenting him on how athletic he was (he was jumping around before). there are better conversation staers than that. shoutout to all of you who have been emotionally abused like that before! stay strong! their opinions do not matter. smile on! ğŸ’ª

text:
2018 is almost over and armageddon is actually upon us this time.

for our next challenge, november 12th, 6 weeks of training with a major goal in focus. an inch on your arms!

theres no time like the present and what better way to end the year than with bigger arms!

this 6-week program is a progression that ramps up the training frequency (how often you train arms each week) starting at once per week in week one; twice per week in week two; and three times per week in weeks three through five. then you back way off in the final week, number six, to just once per week again.

yes, your program includes all the other body parts incorporated into a 4 day split!

trust me, there's a method to this madness.
week one is designed to annihilate your biceps and triceps. you'll pull out all the stops, using negative rep training to really destroy every single muscle fibre you can in your arms.

you'll need a good week to recover from this onslaught. the next week pops your guns with lighter weight and higher reps. volume will be low in these workouts, by design. you'll still be recovering from the previous week.

these workouts will help you to better recover from the previous week and will get you ready for the crazy three weeks that are to come.
in weeks three, four, and five, you will be hitting arms three times per week.

the key is to train to the arms to the point of it almost becoming overtraining and then back off.

that's why you'll be training arms three times per week in weeks three through five and then switch it up to just once per week in week six. i also suggest that the week after week six you take it fairly easy on your arms and train them just once that week before getting back into any serious training programs.

its here, the program that everyone was asking for that will take you into the next year fully loaded.

split week 1 only

workout 1 / arms
workout 2 / legs calves
workout 3 / back & abs
workout 4 / chest, shoulders & traps ğŸ”¥ 6 weeks / $60

i'm dark and i don't believe it. 
but i've to believe it
for the sake of society.
i'm ugly and i don't believe it.
but i've to live with this fact 
for the sake of society.

my mom doesn't want me to tan,
so she applies haldi on me.
my mom wants me to look fair and white,
so she applies face packs on me.

every second i'm being told that 
boys like fair and lovely girls.
everday i'm starving myself
to look skinny and bright with good curves.

they want fifty shades of grey in life
but can't accept fifty shades of shadeism.
they discriminate between light and dark skinned 
and still say they're accepting modernism.

religious shades presented 
rama as fair good king 
fighting the dark evil king ravan.
but we are humans not king or devil
and are still discriminating as demons.

text:
don't die chasing the snake that bit you. 
sometimes we can get so angry at the people who hurt us that we waste time seeking vengeance instead of tending to our wounds. wasting time being fueled by hatred and revenge is a deadly game. it's foolish to expend your energy chasing snakes when what you truly need to be doing is finding help that has the antivenom. 
letting the venom stay in you longer will only cause you more pain and suffering... not the snake. hunting the snake will take you further away from where you need to be going as itÂ slithers away, hides and prepares to attack you again, while you're steady getting weaker from its festering poison. 
majority of snake bites come from people trying to catch snakes. this can correlate to people trying to make any type of wrong relationship work, ignoring their common sense and god given survival instincts. 
don't risk walking around through life half dead because of a bite, limping through it because you had to get an amputation, or enduring nervous system problems because you wasted time focusing on the wrong thing. stop chasing snakes, take care of you, learn your lesson, plan to avoid other snakes at all costs and get back to living aÂ life chasing your dreams and goals instead ğŸ’› . . . . .
